{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614197"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:42:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:42:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16349"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16349"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.17,0,0.07,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9040"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116473"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9040"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16349"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98472"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"6746"},{"type":"tags","id":"7507"},{"type":"tags","id":"7519"},{"type":"tags","id":"9845"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21501"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21503"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116473"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe retina requires extensive venous drainage to maintain proper function and homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the venous drainage pathway of the retina?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Superior ophthalmic vein or directly to cavernous sinus","Inferior ophthalmic vein only","Superior ophthalmic vein only","Pterygoid venous plexus","Direct to cavernous sinus only"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBlood from the retina drains through the branch retinal veins into the central retinal vein. From there, it can drain via two pathways: either through the \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior ophthalmic vein or directly into the cavernous sinus\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior ophthalmic vein\u003C/strong\u003E is not a major drainage pathway for retinal blood. The \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior ophthalmic vein only\u003C/strong\u003E pathway would not account for direct drainage to cavernous sinus. The \u003Cstrong\u003Epterygoid venous plexus\u003C/strong\u003E is not involved in retinal drainage. While \u003Cstrong\u003Edirect drainage to cavernous sinus\u003C/strong\u003E can occur, it is not the only pathway. This dual drainage system provides redundancy and helps maintain consistent venous outflow from the retina, which is crucial for proper retinal function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Retinal venous blood drains via the central retinal vein primarily into the superior ophthalmic vein or directly into the cavernous sinus.","The superior ophthalmic vein is the main venous drainage pathway for the eye and orbital contents."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Bird B, Stawicki SP. Anatomy, Head and Neck, Ophthalmic Arteries. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29493942","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-